Evidence shows that diabetes, specifically type 1 diabetes, compromises the structural integrity of the Achilles tendon through collagen fiber disorganization and increased stiffness. This condition is directly linked to a higher risk of Achilles tendon ruptures and impaired responses under mechanical stress, suggesting reduced resilience during activities like running. Therefore, individuals with type 1 diabetes are likely to have compromised tendon performance during endurance exercises such as a 10 km run.

